body:
@jordanms Thank you for reporting this. Difference in calling patterns would suggest that in some cases polymorphic deserialization is needed (type declared as basetype), whereas in others it is not; but if it is same type, this seems odd.

Now: I think you are right wrt missing handling -- this specific pattern has been added over time, to compensate for problems that occur when buffering content for cases like handling of Type Id, Object Id or unwrapped child objects. So it sounds like at least this specific code path is missing the additional necessary check.

One thing that would be awesome would be a unit test to trigger the problem, but it sounds like it is difficult to reproduce it. But since the problem itself (wrt low level handling) is something I understand, no the need for, not having a test does not prevent fix in this case.

issue.body:
JSOG has been a life saver for our project backed by Neo4j for eliminating infinite recursion, but we're running into trouble with a Java -> Java transfer over REST between microservices.  Our model follows an Interface -> abstract Class -> Impl class structure, and our JSON needs to be deserialized to an implementing class of the specified abstract class.  I am using JSOGGenerator alongside JsonTypeInfo and the order of parsing seems to be backwards.  Jackson is trying to deserialize the JSON object before JSOG is able to point to the existing ref.

I've put together a unit test that shows the failure.  It's entirely possible that I'm just using the annotations incorrectly, but I thought I'd post it here for review.  Thanks in advance!

``` java
import com.fasterxml.jackson.annotation.JsonIdentityInfo;
import com.fasterxml.jackson.annotation.JsonSubTypes;
import com.fasterxml.jackson.annotation.JsonTypeInfo;
import com.fasterxml.jackson.databind.ObjectMapper;
import com.voodoodyne.jackson.jsog.JSOGGenerator;
import org.junit.Test;

/**
 * Created by aaronstone on 1/8/16.
 */
public class JSOGDeserializeAbstractTest {

    /**
     * the key of the property that holds the ref
     */
    public static final String REF_KEY = "@ref";

    /**
     * Reference for string matching.
     */
    private static final String TEST_USER = "TEST_USER";

    /**
     * JSON input
     */
    private static final String USER_JSOG = "{\"@id\":\"1\",\"type\":\"" + TEST_USER + "\",\"user\":{\"@ref\":\"1\"}}";

    ObjectMapper mapper = new ObjectMapper();

    /**
     * Abstract base class.
     */
    @JsonIdentityInfo(generator = JSOGGenerator.class)
    @JsonTypeInfo(
            use = JsonTypeInfo.Id.NAME,
            include = JsonTypeInfo.As.PROPERTY,
            property = "type",
            visible = true)
    @JsonSubTypes({
            @JsonSubTypes.Type(value = UserImpl.class, name = TEST_USER)
    })
    public static abstract class User {

        public String type;
        public User user;

        public User() {
            this.type = getUserType();
        }

        public abstract String getUserType();

    }

    /**
     * Implementing class that should be instantiated via the "type" field.
     */
    public static class UserImpl extends User {

        public UserImpl() {
            super();
        }

        public String getUserType() {
            return TEST_USER;
        }
    }

    @Test
    public void testAbstractDeserialization() throws Exception {
        User user = mapper.readValue(USER_JSOG, User.class);
        assert user.type.equals(TEST_USER);
    }
}
```

